                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                <head>No. 54.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Putnam</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Blaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-07-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">July</hi> 18, 1881</date>. (Received July
                        30.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 84.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to state that Mr. Frère,
                    director-general of the foreign office, called upon me at the legation on the
                    16th instant. Referring to the interview narrated in my dispatch No. 74, he said
                    that the statement he then made was informal, but that he now called, by
                    instruction of the minister of foreign affairs, to state to me officially that
                    His Majesty the King of Belgium, when officially informed of his selection as
                    arbitrator under the treaty between Costa Rica and Colombia, would decline that
                    trust. * * *</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JAMES O. PUTNAM.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
